benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/invoicePayments/{paymentId}/tags - Remove tags from payment

covered: DELETE - Valid Deletion: Multiple success paths returning 204 (all tags, single tagDef, multiple tagDef, optional headers, no tags on payment).
DELETE - Non-Existent Resource: 404 when paymentId does not exist.
DELETE - Concurrency: Concurrent delete requests handled gracefully.
Input validation: 400 for invalid paymentId format and invalid tagDef; injection attempts rejected.
Headers: Required X-Killbill-CreatedBy enforced (missing -> 400); optional Reason/Comment accepted; audit logging verified.
Query parameters: tagDef optional and multi-valued (collectionFormat=multi) covered; extra unexpected parameter tolerated.
Data consistency: Post-deletion GET reflects updated tags.
Operational resilience: 503 (service unavailable) and 504 (timeout) covered; high-volume performance scenario included.
gaps: Soft delete semantics: No explicit verification whether removals are soft-deleted/tombstoned versus hard removal (if applicable per system behavior).
Response headers: No assertions for Content-Type (Produces: application/json) on error responses; no explicit checks for correct headers with 204 (e.g., absence of body).
Idempotency and duplicates: No test for repeating the same DELETE producing the same 204 outcome; no handling of duplicate tagDef values in a single request.
Mixed-valid tagDef list: Scenario with a mixture of valid UUIDs and invalid values in one request is missing to confirm full rejection versus partial delete.
Authorization granularity: No 403 Forbidden/role-based permission scenarios; only 401 is covered.
Boundary limits: No explicit upper-bound tests (e.g., maximum tagDef count allowed, very long X-Killbill-CreatedBy/Reason/Comment values, Unicode/encoding edge cases).
Strict parsing of collectionFormat=multi: No scenario ensuring comma-separated single parameter is rejected vs. multiple parameters being required.
recommendations: Add idempotency scenarios: repeat DELETE on already tag-less payment and with same tagDef set; include duplicate tagDef values to ensure de-duplication and stable 204.
Add mixed-valid tagDef test (one invalid among valid) to verify behavior (expected 400 and no partial deletions).
Assert response headers: verify Content-Type: application/json for 4xx/5xx and that 204 has no body; optionally assert no Content-Type for 204 if that is the contract.
Clarify deletion model; if soft-delete applies, add tests to verify tombstoning/history and retrieval via audit endpoints (and no hard removal).
Introduce authorization/permission tests returning 403 for users lacking tag-removal rights (if applicable).
Add boundary and robustness tests: maximum allowed tagDef entries (and 413/400 when exceeded), very long/Unicode CreatedBy/Reason/Comment, and invalid encodings.
Add a negative test to ensure collectionFormat=multi is enforced (reject comma-separated lists in a single tagDef parameter).
